text:
recy taylor (n√©e corbitt; december 31, 1919 ‚Äì december 28, 2017) was an african-american woman from abbeville in henry county, alabama, u.s. she was born and raised in a sharecropping family in the jim crow era southern united states. taylor's refusal to remain silent about a brutal rape she suffered, perpetrated by white men, led to organizing in the african-american community on behalf of justice and civil rights. on september 3, 1944, taylor was kidnapped while leaving church and gang-raped by six white men. despite the men's confessions to authorities, two grand juries subsequently declined to indict the men; no charges were ever brought against her assailants. in 2011, the alabama legislature officially apologized on behalf of the state "for its failure to prosecute her attackers." taylor's rape, refusal to remain silent, and the subsequent court cases were among the early instances of nationwide protest and activism among the african-american community, and ended up providing an organizational spark in the civil rights movement. at the 2018 golden globe awards, while accepting the golden globe cecil b. demille award, oprah winfrey discussed and brought awareness to taylor's story. the congressional black caucus led democratic caucus members in wearing red "recy" pins while attending the 2018 state of the union, where taylor's granddaughter, mary joyce owens, was a guest. 
#blackhistory #blackhistorymonth #proudtobeblack #blacklivesmatter #institutionalizedracism #intersectionalfeminism #recytaylor #metoo #timesup #blackrapevictimsmatter #civilrights #civilrightsactivist #civilrightsarehumanrights #blackhistoryshouldbecelebratedallyearlong #blackhistoryisamericanhistory #blackwomenmatter #blackwomeninamerica #blackgirlmagic #blackgirlsrock

text:
let's talk apps!! part 1...
last week we asked parents when was the last time they checked their child's cell phone for inappropriate or questionable apps. this week we are dedicating our discussions to highlighting a few of the apps that might be problematic for your kids to use due to the potential access that sexual predators will have to them while using these apps. apps like facebook, instagram, and twitter are recognized by most parents and as common as they may be in the social media conversation, these apps  pose a significant risk to minors due to their direct messaging features. however, there are other apps that can be problematic as well. there are also apps known as "phantom" or "ghost" apps that have seemingly innocuous uses like a calculator for example. but, they are in fact hidden repositories for pictures and messages, and these are  photos and messages that your child won't want you to see. predators encourage kids to use these hidden apps so they can share pornographic material with your child. and, with the development and release of new apps all the time, parents must become more tech savvy and aware of what's on their child's phone. you should be especially interested in apps that are taking up a significant amount of space on your child's phone. instructions on how to check this and exactly what you should be looking for is provided in the attached article. stay tuned for info on specific apps and why you should be concerned! #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #rapevictim #victim #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate #volunteer #activist #superbowl @pros4youth

maya angelou has said many things that strike and beguile me. she continues to be one of my biggest inspirations as a woman and a writer. .
.
"i've learned that people will forget what you said, people will forget what you did, but people will never forget the way you made them feel." .
.
i ruminated on this today. 
i want to leave a good feeling. 
and regardless of circumstance
that's entirely up to me. 
happy monday!

text:
monday motivation.

sitting with clients i often hear their desire to become normal. normal in their sleep patterns, normal in the abcence of chronic pain, normal in outlook and thoughts, normal in physical appearance. perhaps all of us, at some point, hold a strong want and desire to feel connected to our tribe. after all these years and evolutionary changes we are still a tribal species. there is comfort or safety in the numbers at times of risk or threat. a child who is raised by the villagers does benefit from the diversity of styles and influences. to use or substitute a standard reference like normal is dangerous and a means to control the masses. 
we know, especially over the last 10 to 15 years and our awakening over subjects like #metoo movement, that what was considered normal as recently as 30 to 50 years ago no longer holds any water today in the acceptability column on how we treat people. 
what was normal, on how we treated others based on the colour of their skin and it was that which determined where and what you could do has long been established as not acceptable nor right. 
being pleasantly plump verging on a little larger than that was considered normal and desirable and a few generations later looking skinny and gaunt were the norm. 
having tattoos were considered normal for sailors not the general public and now a vast majority of our world have some ink applied. 
hell at one point in time thinking that the earth was flat and sailors would fear for thier lives in sailing over the edge was normal. 
there could never be a template for normal as all of us get to contribute. as all of us are unique and have different views and perspectives, not one can ve considered the standard  to create a environment that holds and judges you to an ambiguous concept and labels it "normal" is spinning propaganda and selling something.

you are your very own version of normal. 
be well 
#ednhypnotherapy #selfcare #hypnosis #mindfulness #yegtherapist #happiness #mondaymotivation #indivdualism #beautifulwithin #youarebeautiful
name: ednhypnotherapy

hell at one point in time thinking that the eah was flat and sailors would fear for thier lives in sailing over the edge was normal. 
there could never be a template for normal as all of us get to contribute. as all of us are unique and have different views and perspectives, not one can ve considered the standard  to create a environment that holds and judges you to an ambiguous concept and labels it "normal" is spinning propaganda and selling something.

you are your very own version of normal. 
be well

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided repos about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

here's the rundown for the week:‚†Ä
‚†Ä
monday - update your memberships‚†Ä
tuesday - update your profiles ‚†Ä
wednesday - change all your headers‚†Ä
thursday - evaluate your conference participation ‚†Ä
friday - evaluate the planner situation ‚†Ä
* ‚†Ä
come see each day what i'm talking about as well as some helpful tips to assist you with your own stuff. ‚†Ä
*‚†Ä
first thing is memberships. are you currently enrolled in any professional organizations. some of them are super duper awesome and some well you know, like anything else, i will protect the guilty by not naming. if you want to know what i am a member of which means one of two things, 1. i'm a new member and i'm evaluating or 2. i'm a long term member and i find it very useful... those are the two keys but i came up with this little short list of things that can make memberships useful or not and as such they can help you determine if the price is right. ‚†Ä
* ‚†Ä
see 9 points to consider whether you should pay that price to join‚†Ä
*‚†Ä
do they...‚†Ä
1. have a #socialmedia presence‚†Ä
2.  #classes / workshops / webinars ‚†Ä
3. #newsletter‚†Ä
4.  #speakers - live events and online‚†Ä
5. annual #conference/ retreat‚†Ä
6.  scholarships to make attendance possible to #6‚†Ä
7.  clout or industry pull - when push comes to shove‚†Ä
8. receptive - i‚Äôve been in a lot of groups and sometimes i‚Äôm in the minority, a nice way of saying. it's fine if there is not a larger systemic issue. but do you sense that they have their token, are there clique-ish, and have bullies that send people packing, and are they discuss such issues and plan to welcome diversity? ‚†Ä
9. do they follow (and have) protocols - i haven‚Äôt thought about this until this last 2 years honestly, and probably should be # 1, but in #metoo era, groups are flying blindly. i‚Äôm talking harassment, anti discrimination, confidentiality policy, accessibility, grievance policy, fair voting/bylaws‚†Ä
*‚†Ä
what are reasons u decide to join? leave in the comments...

some stories are met with remorse or empathy, but ultimately there is no justice. 
how do we get justice for these women?

#  new york times places songwriter ryan adams in the crosshairs of its #metoo witch hunt by eric london 18 february 2019 alt-country singer/songwriter ryan adams has become a target of the #metoo witch hunt, the latest ‚Äúpublic enemy of the week‚Äù in the right-wing campaign orchestrated in the pages of the filthy new york times. in a major spread in thursday‚Äôs print edition, which was posted prominently on the front page of the on-line edition, the times features an article headlined ‚Äúryan adams dangled success. women say they paid a price,‚Äù by entertainment writers joe coscarelli and melena ryzik. the article is a vindictive personal attack on the musician. it alleges‚Äîwithout factual support‚Äîthat adams pressured women into sexual relationships as a quid pro quo for promises of record deals and stardom. ryan adams within hours, the music industry began erasing adams‚Äô nearly 30-year career as a pioneer of popular americana music. retail companies indefinitely postponed the release of his forthcoming album ‚Äúbig colors‚Äù and radio corporations are blacklisting his latest single, which had been climbing the charts as late as wednesday. the ceos of benson amplifiers, walrus audio and jhs pedals all issued statements dropping sponsorship of adams-branded equipment.‚Ä¶

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

bannon's attorney william burck did not immediately respond to an email request for comment on wylie's testimony.

wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text: i got lucky and slipped into this hunky photo: #prgirlisoke rising up the #mensfashion scene: #agreatdayindc. sometimes fashion can be silly or frivolous, but i'm realizing more and more that it's central to cultural change. it's how we feel powerful, sexy, and humble. i've been trying to be gentle and humble, listening more, and dealing with shame and ways that i continue to be selfish and toxic. i promise to add my feminine fury into modern masculinity and work to confront the ways i've been a part of the problem. #metoo cannot only be finally rooting out the "monsters" and "predators". this is not the work of unfucking masculinity, it is only passing the buck. hopefully these hunks and i can challenge our fellow dc men and beyond to confront shame and failure, lose powerfully, and bring up a new generation of gentle men. culture is politics. i wanna make politics suck less, so fashion is a literally beautiful way to make that happen. #bringthenoise

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the colored girls museum will launch her spring campaign and exhibition, ‚Äúin search of the colored girl,‚Äù on sunday march 3, 2019 coinciding with women‚Äôs history month. 
in search of the colored girl,‚Äù is the colored girls‚Äô museum fourth exhibition since it opened in march 2015. the colored girls museum is the first and only institution of its kind to document and celebrate the ordinary, extraordinary colored girl . the current campaign and exhibition considers movements like #metoo, #muterkelly,  the adultification of black girls and the erasure of contributions of black women and girls from important movements and history. we also consider the nearly 75,000 black girls and women missing across the country. ‚Äúin a docent led tour of the exhibit ‚Äúin search of the colored girl‚Äù patrons will become the ‚Äúsearch party.‚Äù the museum an excavation site and visual travelogue. visitors must search for the colored girl she has gone missing. they can search for her in her kitchen, a bedroom perhaps they will find her in a photo album or favorite book. maybe she is hidden in a closet or an old laundry basket . is she in an action hero collection her music or favorite scent.  is she a chair covered in hair? 
each installation, work of art or artifact is evidence that she does exist, no matter how much she is excluded or overlooked. who is she? where was she seen last? who did she talk to?  what was she wearing? when was she reported missing, or was she? did she have a best friend, a favorite book or place to visit? what are the consequences of our silence around her disappearance?
featured artwork
janet taylor pickett - paper dolls 
debbie lerman - photography 
victoria edwards - graphic design

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
thursday, february 21 at 11:30am, college for creative studies fine arts department talk series and ccs international student services will be hosting a university of michigan stamps guest lecture by u-m artist residence juyeon kim. this talk series lecture is open to all ccs students, faculty, and staff.

born in seoul, south korea, juyeon kim works and lives in new york. she has shown in both solo and group exhibitions nationally and internationally including new york, washington, dc, shanghai, and seoul. additionally, kim has been awarded several residencies such as macdowell colony, kohler arts center, triangle, and the roswell artist in residence fellowship. kim has also held several positions as a visiting artist and professor. a 2018‚Äì2019 roman witt resident, kim is creating a multimedia installation work in collaboration with the stamps school community and composer george tsontakis that seeks to explore themes around korean ‚Äúcomfort women‚Äù‚Äî the female prisoners of the japanese army during world war ii.  kim states: ‚Äúalthough my installation project was conceived and initiated before my awareness of the #metoo movement developing in the states and around the world, it seems to me to be so poignantly connected to the historical plight of women everywhere. while the travails of the korean ‚Äòcomfort women‚Äô are an extreme example of women‚Äôs integrity being compromised, the assault sadly continues on various levels and by different degrees.‚Äù this lecture is co-sponsored by the u-m nam center for korean studies in association with the university of michigan roman j. witt residency program in collaboration with michigan stamps school of art and design and made possible by the artist in the classroom grant.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

cu devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
this response is typical of the behind-the-scenes responses i get from pastors when speaking about #sbctoo/#churchtoo/#metoo.
.
we need to understand the pressure celebrity pastor culture puts on men to mimic the silence/speech of influencers.
.
there is often an unspoken fear that if we don't speak or refrain from speaking in the ways the heroes of the faith do, then we won't be invited to their conferences, their retreats, their councils, and that we'll be disassociated from the fellowship of their followers.
.
and sometimes, it is a wrongheaded assumption that because these leaders are more intelligent, more popular, and more seasoned, then they must be right on their assessments. so, who am i to disagree.
.
you're a spirit-filled child of god, believer. that's who you are.
.
we need more #menwhospeak. will you?

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
part 3‚Ä¢ #rant #poem 
i‚Äôm taking the day off today. i‚Äôm driving the minivan down to washington d.c., and i‚Äôm going to take a tour of the white house, the house that houses the highest seat in the american government, and i‚Äôm going to co-regulate with my tour group. the kids, the tweens, the 20somethings, the middle aged, the elderly, too. i‚Äôm going to ignite my relaxation response, in effort to curb the shitty talk that streams from the airwaves of this, 2019, white house.  i‚Äôm going to go fully psycho-emotional because i have found that the more i explore my autonomic nervous system, the better i am at being alive and well and living on earth. 
tremoring brings comprehension. it is comprehensive. 
#attuned to me.

#metoo

#alive having survived.

i‚Äôm all about reducing stress and anxiety. first, it was for performing artists,  these precious souls who ignite the world with emotional loving beauty and clarity. and, then, we began to widen, to understand, that this was for every body on the planet earth. artist‚Äôs come into burnt out, bombed out neighborhoods and transform them into dionysian habitats, fit for any trust funded young something or other. we also do this, scientifically. nerogenically. we waltz to the edge of imagination, then report back to the director, the gallerist, the gallery, the curator‚Äî we find cures. we slough off. we slake thirst. we shake things up. #artists
name: Karma, Curated By Betsy Allen

text:
we teach girls to shrink themselves, to make themselves smaller. we say to girls, you can have ambition, but not too much. you should aim to be successful, but not too successful. otherwise, you would threaten the man. because i am female, i am expected to aspire to marriage. i am expected to make my life choices always keeping in mind that marriage is the most important. now marriage can be a source of joy and love and mutual support but why do we teach girls to aspire to marriage and we don‚Äôt teach boys the same? we raise girls to see each other as competitors not for jobs or accomplishments, which i think can be a good thing, but for the attention of men. we teach girls that they cannot be sexual beings in the way that boys are.

chimamanda ngozi adichie, we should all be feminists

we teach girls to shrink themselves, to make themselves smaller. we say to girls, you can have ambition, but not too much. you should aim to be successful, but not too successful. otherwise, you would threaten the man. because i am female, i am expected to aspire to marriage. i am expected to make my life choices always keeping in mind that marriage is the most important. now marriage can be a source of joy and love and mutual support but why do we teach girls to aspire to marriage and we don‚Äôt teach boys the same? we raise girls to see each other as competitors not for jobs or accomplishments, which i think can be a good thing, but for the attention of men. we teach girls that they cannot be sexual beings in the way that boys are.

text:
wahai suami biarkan timbangan kasih istrimu itu tetap adil. berikan dia kebebasan untuk mencintai keluarganya sebagaimana dia juga mencintai keluargamu. karena "perempuan" itu ketika menjadi seorang "istri" maka cintanya memang sudah semestinya terbagi-bagi kemana-mana. baik buruk sikap "istrimu", engkaulah yang menentukannya sendiri. karena aturanmu baginya adalah didikan untuknya bagaimana kelak ia berelasi kembali dengan keluarganya dan dengan keluargamu sendiri. üòé 
hai... kamu @robin_tabaraka @robintabaraka @tabaraka_robin üòç 
aku mau bilang : ... üòä "terima kasih banyak karena telah mengajari aku dan mengarahkanku bagaimana memperlakukan keluargaku, mengasihi, dan menghormati mereka. bagaimana berlaku yang seharusnya dan yang sepantasnya. sebagaimana kamu juga demikian kepada keluargamu sendiri dan keluargaku. aku-pun akan tetap berusaha adil dan mencintai juga menghormati keluargamu. semoga kita bisa sama-sama terus belajar dan berproses menjadi baik, baik, baik, baik, dan lebih baik lagi. amin." üåπüôèüòá #husbands #husbandandwife #wifes #familydinner #familytrip #familytravel #familyguy #thankyougod #catatanpatrice #patrice #patricia #160219 #16022019 #reflection #renungan #loveit #lover #loved #familylove #lovefamily #philosophy #philosophyoflife #relationshipquotes #wearefamily #youandmeforever #ourstory #myfamily #metoo #gratefulheart #thankyou

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
#truth healthy relationships start with yourself and with god. 
dysfunctional relationships are killers...dream robbers, purpose robbers, self-esteem robbers, peace robbers, joy robbers....god put us here to fulfill purpose, to fulfill his will.  we underestimate the importance of healthy relationships. we either soar & fly because of them or sadly, many become a slave to dysfunctional relationships, give up on themselves, their dreams, become complacent, stagnant and never see who god created them to be. "a man" won't change your life, the committment of a great man will....a friendship won't be your source, but a real friendship will make you even better and stronger...great relationships propel you into your destiny...unhealthy relationships rob us. period. i'm grateful to have learned this lesson.  if you love me, you truly want me to win.

you will make mistakes, you will fall and get back up again. people will walk in and out of your life, and while you may feel like you can‚Äôt go on without them you can and you will. you will have your heart broken, you will be taken advantage of and played a fool, but through these tribulations you will learn the value of good people.you will struggle with trying to define yourself. you will become the person you think other people want you to be and confuse these false ideals with who you are. once you let go and stop caring what other people think of you that is when you‚Äôll truly be free to be you....

#
by lucia binding, news reporter dolly parton has said there is still "a long way to go" for women in the workplace as she addressed gender equality before the launch of 9 to 5 the musical in london.the country music star said 9 to 5 the musical, which debuted at the west end's savoy theatre on sunday, deals with some "great, important issues" and that the show resonates with the recent #metoo movement. speaking to sky news, she said: "it's a work in progress as life itself is - especially women in the workplace. image: dolly parton sits down with sky news to discuss some of the issues addressed in the show "so i really think that's why we're here now with the new #metoo movement."it brought up the subject again with harassment in the workplace and the fact that women are still not getting the chance to do as much as they can or get paid equal for the work that they do." parton, who wrote the grammy award-winning song 9 to 5 in the 70s, said she was "lucky" to have navigated a successful career but admitted to being constantly "hit on" throughout her life.she said: "of course‚Ä¶

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text:
i realized i was attracted to men at the age of 4. i didn‚Äôt know whether it was normal for me to feel so or was it socially acceptable. but like anyone else, i thought it‚Äôs a phase which would eventually pass with time. but, when that didn‚Äôt happen, i came out of the closet - at the age of 18.

this is my story.

the only reason i believe i was able to do so at the age of 18 was because i was provided and was brought up in an environment which was safe. as much as i would like to thank my family for that, when i look back as a teenager, it was annoying and irritating to have someone watch you like a hawk. but it is only now i understand why they were the way they were.

among many folks that i have had conversations with about child sexual abuse, the incident happened at home - a place that we consider safe, by those people whom we actually call family. as sad as it sounds, the truth is disheartening and the fact that matters like these are often swept under the carpet because ‚Äòlog kya kahenge‚Äô (what will people say)?
being queer is such a wonderful feeling. but it is saddening to know that most people identify themselves as lesbian, gay, bisexual and queer because of the traumatizing experiences from their childhood. physically and mentally hurt, the rainbow turns grey and the void in their hearts are filled with nothing but numbness.

in the frame: a handwritten post from monica mayer‚Äôs work ‚Äòthe clothesline‚Äô.begun in 1978 in mexico city as a response to what she disliked the most about the city, this iteration has participants write their experiences of sexual harassment, hung on a clothesline, replicating the domestic act of hanging laundry that many women share. initiated forty years ago, it was marked relevant with the heightened visibility of sexual abuse allegations and the activism of #metoo, mayer creates a safe space for comradeship to form when people read and respond to each other‚Äôs anonymous reflections, as not everyone has the social privilege or security to speak up about their injustices publicly.

edited on @lightroom

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company ‚Äúweaponised‚Äù the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how users‚Äô preferences for particular brands on social media platforms ‚Äì facebook, in particular ‚Äì were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaign‚Äôs lesser reported ‚Äúweapons of mass destruction‚Äù. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someone‚Äôs personality. a user‚Äôs predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call ‚Äúpopulist political signalling‚Äù. cambridge analytica, which was¬†shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trump‚Äôs former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 ‚Äì including cultural preferences such as fashion and music ‚Äì to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
for those 87 million people probably wondering what was actually done with their data, i went back to christopher wylie, the ex-cambridge analytica employee who blew the whistle on the company‚Äôs problematic operations in the observer. according to wylie, all you need to know is a little bit about data science, a little bit about bored rich women, and a little bit about human psychology.

step one, he says, over the phone as he scrambles to catch a train: - when you‚Äôre building an algorithm, you first need to create a training set. that is: no matter what you want to use fancy data science to discover, you first need to gather the old-fashioned way. before you can use facebook likes to predict a person‚Äôs psychological profile, you need to get a few hundred thousand people to do a 120-question personality quiz.

the ‚Äútraining set‚Äù refers, then, to that data in its entirety: the facebook likes, the personality tests, and everything else you want to learn from. most important, it needs to contain your ‚Äúfeature set‚Äù: - the underlying data that you want to make predictions on, wylie says. - in this case, it‚Äôs facebook data, but it could be, for example, text, like natural language, or it could be clickstream data ‚Äì the complete record of your browsing activity on the web. - those are all the features that you want to [use to] predict. at the other end, you need your target variables, the things that you‚Äôre trying to predict for. so in this case, personality traits or political orientation, or what have you.

alex hern
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - i‚Äôve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now i‚Äôm about to go back, knowing what i know, and we‚Äôre about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trump‚Äôs election, trumpeted the return of their ‚Äúpopulist hero‚Äù on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publication‚Äôs announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if there‚Äôs any confusion out there, let me clear it up: i‚Äôm leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents ‚Äì on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text: happy birthday to me! every year it snows on my birthday and reading up about what snow represents it now all makes since. this last year has been the hardest of my life. it is the year i decided i was tired of surviving and i went threw the work to heal. i have triumphed threw a sexual assault as a 16 year old, a gang rape when i was 23, having a son with a man who chose abandon us with nothing and watching a close friend get shot 3 times. i don't say this for sympathy i say this because i am proud of myself for choosing me. for excepting my trauma and knowing that i am so much more. threw this choice to love myself i have to a new reality. one that is so foreign that i have yet to find my balance. but i am well on my way to the loving joyful life i deserve. so this year i welcome the snow. because it is truly a new beginning a day cleansed of all trauma and survival. because now i am living!! #snow #birthday #growth #proud #strangth #survival #selflove #newbeginning #indurence #metoo @anthonydbrice  read more about snow: https://www.meaningfullife.com/spiritual-meaning-snow/

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

text:
i was 18
i had just lost my father
i was vulnerable and in need of support
i considered him a friend
i opened up to him

he offered his company
he brought alcohol
he kept my glass full
he pretended to listen
he violated me

and some days, where everything is great, a thing happens unexpectedly, that sets me back to that one night in august 2003. 
but i'm not going to give up. you have no control over me. not anymore.

text: one year ago today, i went public with my rape. i made the full version of this video, @madeline.magee posted it, and along came weeks of tears, hugs, messages, and calls of support. i decided to tell the world about my most vulnerable thing so that i could be a voice for the voiceless. for the ones who never got a chance to tell their story, or the ones who are still in silence. for the ones who need a reminder that someone else has been where they are. today i am reminded of how i felt 365 days ago, and there will really never be anything like it. this was the first day on my true road to recovery. the first day i decided to take my life back. i thought it was only fitting to post this again in honor of the millions of others i am a part of. here we are- living, despite it all. üñ§ #metoo

text:
at first i wasn‚Äôt sure what to write as a caption but i‚Äôve been watching law and order svu (sexual assaulted based crimes) and i think i want to talk about that. so fair warning to anyone this may cause triggers. 
i have been sexually molested/assaulted in many different ways and by two different people. one a male and one a female. when i was in elementary school i had a best friend and her and i started doing sexual things and i went along with it because i didn‚Äôt know any better. it was obvious she was learning these things from home so i and my family never fully blamed her, for she was only a year or two older than me. 
that situation started a very early development towards sexual interests. i started watching porn and touching myself while i was still in elementary school. my therapist helped me realize that this was my first sexual relationship (as tough as that is to understand) and that is why i claim as bisexual but never really talk about it because i don‚Äôt see a reason why someone‚Äôs sexuality matters. 
the second person was my first serious boyfriend who would beat me if i refused to have sex with him. he also anally raped me. there is more i could go into but it‚Äôs not worth my time because he is nothing but an evil memory to me. 
what i‚Äôm trying to say is i have been through the works. i know what it‚Äôs like. i know what it‚Äôs like to feel like you are disgusting for letting it happen and you hate yourself and your body. but you must grow from that and cherish your body instead and be thankful you‚Äôre still alive and healthy (as you can be).‚ô•Ô∏è #bodypositive #metoo #advocate

text:
you were supposed to be
my first love, but alcohol
was your only love
you went missing in plain sight

i searched for you in men (boys)
who were looking to
bury their shame between my legs

i was 14, he was 23
you were nowhere, he was there
2 am at my window
i walked into my abusers arms
willingly

no was not an answer
that could pass through my lips
i didn‚Äôt know it was wrong
when my body shook, cold in the grass
when the vomit came as he did
when he said he was my friend now
not my coach

where were you
which bottle did you crawl down that night
the night i looked for you
and found the start of my unraveling -jhm // are you my father

please take caution!!!! ...........................‚Ä¶‚Ä¶............................................................ the other day marked 3 years since i was drugged and sexually assaulted. it somehow feels both like a lifetime ago & like ‚Äúoh god... that was only three years ago?‚Äù i ran away from the pain for a long time. at first, it was for survival purposes. i could not comprehend what had happened to me and there was no way to wrap my mind around it. so i passed the time with vices and distractions. but the pain got trapped deep inside me, and it began to eat away. and suddenly, the problem was everywhere around me with no escape. the damage began to surface and there was no more denying what happened. so i decided it was time to face the most sickening pain i‚Äôve known. sooo i found a therapist. i took the leap. she is kind, insightful, nurturing. she has begun helping me process something that i avoided. i‚Äôm letting go of so much pain but tonight i feel the weight, and had a bit of a heavy session. so i dance. i will dance and do yoga until all the anger inside me is gone and there‚Äôs nothing but love. my world was once violated. in fact, this very moment 3 years ago i thought i was going to die. but i know the person i was before, and what she faced has brought me to where i am today. so old sydney, wherever you are in the universe, i‚Äôm so sorry for what he did to you. i‚Äôm so sorry he made you not trust the world. just know i don‚Äôt love you any less & in fact i love you more for your strength. if you took the time to read this, thank you for listening to my story. if you are in this unfortunate statistic with me, my spirit is hugging you. this world can be a really dark place but i‚Äôm convinced there‚Äôs got to be just as much light. ‚ù§Ô∏è#metoo

text:
i don‚Äôt know ryan adams, but i‚Äòve listened to his music for the past ten years. i stopped listening to him about a year ago after i heard something @_fake_nudes_ said about him from the stage during a show in austin, the same thing she spoke out about this week alongside six other women in a @nytimes article. thank you to these women for their bravery, and to all people that come forward with their stories of abuse and sexual misconduct.

i‚Äôm discouraged that industries fueled by art have so many stories like ryan adams. people abuse their power by dangling success in front of vulnerable artists through sexual advances and emotional abuse. i feel like i can‚Äôt do anything about this behavior, and i think we often feel this way when we aren‚Äôt actively on the other side of making art within these systems.

but, we can do something about it. we can change culture and stand alongside female artists, supporting them in their work. we can create a space that removes exploitation and replaces it with encouragement. i want to be part of this change by echoing @iamreginaking, pledging that 50% of the art, music, film, shows, and books i consume this year will be from female creators and makers. as i do this, i‚Äôll share posts here on instagram featuring lady musicians, writers, filmmakers, photographers, bloggers, influencers, actors, and makers. art is how we use our voice, and i want to remind women to continue to use their voice. ‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
in an israeli paper today. litzman and leifer. what do you think? 
#bringleiferback
-
malka leifer, my former school principal is under custody in israel but is claiming mental illness in order to avoid extradition. 
meanwhile in australia she has 74 charges of sexual assault to face and numerous victims waiting for a chance to face her in court. 
it's been found that the corruption reaches all the way to the israeli goverment with health minister litzman alleged to have pressured psychiatrists to state leifer was unfit to stand trial. 
for more information on my campaign for justice visit my facebook page - dassi erlich; beyond a survivor

chapter 17
pinnacles
it was june 28th 1996, two days before my twentieth birthday. i woke up to birds chirping out of my window of the parents home. the parents had planned to bring arrian with to my grandmothers for the weekend, so we needed to be home so i could pack her things, and give her kisses good-bye. she wasn‚Äôt all smiles that morning as she had gotten her immunizations the day prior, but still never cried, arrian again got super baby marks from the doctor as she was so advanced for her 6 month age, already standing and trying to walk around her playpen. st and i would be meeting them at the grandmothers in the evening. we had planned to spend the day at valley fair (an amusement park) for my birthday gift. my younger cousin mw had flown in from washington the night before, so they would also be bringing her with.
we thank you, 
gorsl

it was june 28th 1996, two days before my twentieth bihday. i woke up to birds chirping out of my window of the parents home. the parents had planned to bring arrian with to my grandmothers for the weekend, so we needed to be home so i could pack her things, and give her kisses good-bye. she wasn‚Äôt all smiles that morning as she had gotten her immunizations the day prior, but still never cried, arrian again got super baby marks from the doctor as she was so advanced for her 6 month age, already standing and trying to walk around her playpen. st and i would be meeting them at the grandmothers in the evening. we had planned to spend the day at valley fair (an amusement park) for my bihday gift. my younger cousin mw had flown in from washington the night before, so they would also be bringing her with.
we thank you, 
gorsl

text:
theres beauty that resides deep in its bones of her. her heart to give to others fortunate or less fortunate. her ability to use her heart as a lion. her ability to unconditional love her family. 
her beauty comes in creativity and beautifying women through cooking, through makeup, through empowering change and cracking your soul open with humor.

she looks pain, failure ,defeat, injustice, mistreatment and disloyalty in its eyes and say like maya angelou poem, " i rise". she say like george benard shaw "you dream dreams and i say why not?" she brought my stirring of my creativity from my heart to the external.

women thank every woman that brings, unconditional  love, beauty, joy, peace, empowering actions, kind words, inner growth and unconditional diversity in your life.

leslie, i thank you from my beauty empowerment to your beauty empowerment.üåπüíï my cup runneth..üíó #womensempowerment

text: i hear almost everyday ‚Äúfocus on your why‚Äù or ‚Äúwhat is your why‚Äù. i‚Äôve always said  that i want to be the person i once needed, which is still true, but even more than that is i want to be that person plus so much more for this little girl. she‚Äôs my 4 year old baby cousin. she looks up to me and loves me so much and sometimes i forget about how much of an impact i have on her. to her i am her best friend, her role model, and her amazing older cousin that can do no wrong. she is such a vibrant and innocent soul. after seeing her today and the way she talked to me and told me about her crazy little 4 year old life, it‚Äôs quickly made me realize i have to be better. i have to be a better friend, a better stylist, a better daughter, a better cousin, and a better me. i‚Äôve always been a strong believer in putting yourself first and doing what‚Äôs best for you, but when you have a little person in your life who looks up to you for everything you do, you need to recognize that your decisions and actions affect them too. so yes, my why is still to be the person for someone that i once needed, but now it‚Äôs also i want to be that person for her, and prioritize my relationships with the little people in my life. at the end of the day, they‚Äôre gonna be around longer than us, and we set the example for them. so yes, put yourself first and do what‚Äôs best for you, but every so often check the mirror and see if your reflection matches how you want the little people in your life to see you! they‚Äôre little sponges and they absorb everything, and all i want my mini me to absorb everything good i bring into her life.üíóüë≠

text:
this question always comes up on our host calls: ‚Äúwill the men at my company be able to identify with the stories in the film?‚Äù dream, girl gives men the unique opportunity to view the world through a woman‚Äôs perspective. they get to hear about the challenges, discrimination, and experiences women face in a one-hour documentary that‚Äôs upbeat and uplifting. we‚Äôve had everyone from nasa engineers to republican representatives gush over how inspiring these stories are. it‚Äôs a great way to bring the men and women in your company in conversation about what they can do to support and uplift one another.
pro tip: if you do host a panel or q&a alongside the film make sure you let the women in your company lead. in 100% of the screenings i attend if there is one man in the audience he will ask the first question and lead the discussion. this is a great opportunity for the guys to sit back, listen, and let the women in your company be the authority on their experiences. don‚Äôt feel like having men be part of the conversation for your event? that‚Äôs cool too! curate your screening in a way that best serves your audience and your intention for hosting.
‚Ä¶

text:
the me too movement was a hard one for me to jump on. but here i am, jumping.
speak to your children about sexual abuse. my mom did. she told me no one was allowed to touch my body, and if anyone ever did, to tell her. 
it's too bad that 2 cousins of mine, chose not to touch my body (that i remember), but force me to touch theirs. they are only a few years older than me, so for a long time i believed them when they said "we" would get in trouble if i told. like my 4-6 year old self wanted to touch them, with my hands or my mouth. 
my mom didn't cover this, and who thought things like this would need to be covered?

speak to your babies. tell them the dangers. kids are being abused sexually way more than us adults would like to think about. 
my main goal as a mom, is to raise polite, smart kids, who were never molested or raped. 
how sad is that, that it is one of my main goals?
talk to your babies. 
#metoo #childhoodsexualassault #oralrapeisstillrape #talkaboutit
