text:
you'll all grown up now, but inside you there is the innocence, trust, openness of a child. a place of ecstatic joy. let yourself come back to it. you're being called.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
the ista level 1 in bali (16-22 march) helps you return to that open-hearted place.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
here's a peak into the one-week journey:‚†Ä
‚†Ä
// stop, feel and take a look at yourself in a whole new way. this is an opportunity to wake up to your life.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// remember how to love yourself, to feel the healing power of pleasure and expand your sexuality and orgasmic potential.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// learn to experience and create healthy sexual, loving and connected intimate experiences. no more being stuck in your mind, fearing others, or repeating same patterns.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// begin to deeply heal wounds around trauma, sexuality, gender, the body, grief, lost love, self-love, mother and father wounds and other core wounds.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// discover how your inner self (emotion, thoughts, energy) are at war within and be guided to bring yourself back towards inner union, love and integration. no longer enemies with yourself, but lovers! this is huge!‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// tap into the knowledge of your emotions and body, not just your mind.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// learn essential life skills we all should have received as teenagers (sexuality, communication, boundaries, self-love, pleasure practices).‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// come to really believe "i matter"‚Äîembody yourself as a powerful and free sovereign being.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// see, show and live from the you that lies beneath the mask. expressing who you really are beyond the guilt, fear and shame we've picked up from parents, culture, religion and society.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
// meet and explore your edges in a safe container.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä
.ista level 1. @ista_tribe ‚†Ä
16-22 march‚†Ä
bali, villa boreh‚†Ä
more info + reserve your place via my profile.‚†Ä
.‚†Ä

june 16, 2018 i was sexually assaulted. one week later, i found out i contracted hsv-ii. from this event, i became an alcoholic, barely graduated my last semester, i suffered from severe depression, ptsd and suicidal thoughts and attempts. i still live with this burden daily and each day i‚Äôm surviving. 
so before anyone goes around calling me a ‚Äúslut,‚Äù or ‚Äúdirty,‚Äù or yells around that i have ‚Äúherpes,‚Äù i figured i‚Äôd beat them all to the chase since everyone wants to throw low blows. 
my scars are my asset. i‚Äôm not defined by what happened, i‚Äôm driven by it. mind you, i‚Äôm giving you a reason to remember my name.

text:
#bodydigging #golddigging #bodydigger (2 posts) #golddigger (218,088 posts) #doublestandards #metoo #feminism #hijab #mateselection #bodyobjectification #heterosexual #dating

why is it okay for a man to be a body digger, but it isn't okay for a woman to be a gold digger?

even though studies on mate selection, state that heterosexual men value women's bodies (their #beauty, #sexuality, and #fertility) most when selecting a mate -- they seem to have little self-awareness as to this fact. especially when the comparable practice for a woman values most a man's resources and ability to protect, is severley put down.

it's unlikely that any one person's body or resources is going to satisfy everybody in the whole world. and it's likely that few people are going to like being valued for their body (women)  or resources (men) unless they are engaging in the exchange theory. people like sex workers, sugar daddies and sugar mamas, sugar babies and sugar boys are upfront about this exchange and i make no moral judgment. i think people should go after what they want. but what really irks me is the lack of understanding and awareness of men primarily valuing women's bodies and yet they denounce what women want.

oh yes, she should want him just for his body and maybe his personality. just never want him because he has wealth and status.

considering movies like the prince who pretends that he is a popper because he wants to make sure did the woman doesn't want him for his wealth and status. because who wants to be wanted for these superficial and shallow things? unless it is to benefit them.

and just like the movie shrek and the fat and ugly turning into a beautiful princess - people love the idea of being loved for the things that can't be seen too readily.

so unless you want to be fair about it, and you're okay with a woman taking advantage of your resources and your status - will you please take a moment to think about how your body digging affects women around the world?

text:
sometimes you have to remember where you started!

25 months ago i decided to make a promise to myself. that i would give up chasing fast results & instead turn my focus inward. i promised myself, that from this day forward, i was going to do just one thing every day to love myself. whether it was big or small.

that i was important enough to make myself a priority again. and as the days passed, that 1 thing became 2, then 3, and so on. as i began to see what happened when i showed myself love, it boosted my confidence & self belief. even on days when i didn't feel like i was worthy of love, i still forced myself to do something, because i knew how important & life changing this had become.

and here i am.. 25 months later still fulfilling that promise! along the way i've learned how to create habits that became part of my life, not just "a try me to get instant changes" false promises products.

i've learned that real sustaining changes take time, they take consistency, they take commitment, & patience. it takes freaking hard work & never giving up on yourself. it takes momentum & grit to keep challenging yourself. but it's possible.

if i can change my life, believeeee me when i say so can you! i didn't overhaul my life & get this in a month. i started by 1 small daily promise that grew into more baby steps, that grew into a lifestyle change.

but it all starts with that 1 choice, the hardest one we all have to make. to just start. and i don't mean tomorrow, or after another holiday. or when you feel ready. i mean now. you don't need anything to start showing yourself daily love now.

i can guarantee you, if you start with that 1 small promise & stick to it, you will watch your life change!! you can do it! üòä and if you need any help along the way, you know where to find me! üòò

here's to loving yourself daily & seeing all the possibilities unfold!

#selflove #loveyourself #anxiety #depressiontips #anxietysucks

text:
i can count on one hand the amount of happy days i‚Äôve had in the last twelve months. 
but this picture was taken seconds after the only moment in that entire time when i genuinely laughed. 
the thing about an emu is that its long and bendy neck can stretch its face a metre away from its feet. so when i turned around after talking to a roo, i had no warning i would find this guy draped over me, his face centimetres from mine asking for pellets. 
it‚Äôs silly. but those fuzzy and unhinged eyes made me feel joy for the first time since everything.
my guess is that trauma doesn‚Äôt end with a triumph where your life is back the way it was before. instead, i think there‚Äôs small moments where you feel there could be joy in your new life. 
anyway. i don‚Äôt know how you properly thank emus, but i have a suspicion it involves pellets.
#raperecovery #rapesurvivor #metoo #ibelieveher #emu

text:
i'd like to say something super real. something i've never been open about, and something that has adversely affected the way i enjoy going out with friends.
.
about three years ago i went to a bumpin' party. i drank and mingled and met some interesting people. i had a hard time back then making new friends but this one woman kept bumping into me. she seemed really cool and interesting to talk with, so i hung around her for a while. eventually she brought me another drink and i gladly accepted.
.
twenty minutes later i felt suddenly woozy and tired and so decided to lie down in the guest room. i wasn't aware that she'd spiked my drink. i wasn't consciously thinking that could happen to a man, or that it would ever happen to me. i saw her come in to check on me but my brain was shutting down. the next thing i remember she was on top of me. i couldn't move her, i couldn't think straight, and i couldn't remember where i was.
.
i was scared. i was ashamed.
.
i was being raped.
.
after this incident i stopped going out to bars and parties alone. i felt ashamed that it happened and angry that i could no longer enjoy letting loose and getting drunk with new friends. my old friends would invite me out and i'd decline unless it was a small gathering at one of their houses. i didn't want to drink anymore unless i absolutely trusted the people i was around.
.
i tried to explain what happened once to a person i no longer speak to. she laughed at me. "guys can't get raped." she was invalidating how i felt, so i stayed silent - i was afraid others would say the same.
.
it fucked me up. it fucked up my relationships for the next year and a half. it physically made me not want to have sex anymore, at some points where i couldn't even if i wanted to, which hurt my partners along the way.
.
i no longer drink around people i don't know. i don't have sex with someone unless i trust her, and i tend to move a lot slower and take initiative far less than i used to. but i'm mostly better now - i have a healthier view. i'm excited to grow and experience my current relationship to the fullest.
.
just know:

guys can get raped, too.

text: saturday morning found me in a thornton park @starbucks with one of my best friends, her fianc√©, and their wedding photographers. amidst the excitement of their upcoming ceremony and our discussion around day-of specifics, i grabbed the @nytimes and was pleased to see an article written regarding ryan adams‚Äô album cancellation. although this issue has been given new life and new light in recent months thanks to the incredible #metoo and #timesup movements, it‚Äôs as important as ever to acknowledge that this reckoning has been brewing for decades now, spurred on by the defiance of honest and brave survivors who were demanding justice and accountability back when this issue was still overwhelmingly kept in the dark. today, we are able to follow those footpaths and forge the future of justice. we have a long journey ahead in the fight for justice for survivors of sexual abuse and we know that journey will include both the good and bad days, but yesterday was a good one. the wider the conversation spreads, the higher the demand for accountability will be‚Äîand the sooner justice will be served.

text:
the next time you think, "why does god let bad things happen?" think about this...
-
jesus was two miles away from lazarus when he heard his friend was sick. two miles. he could've been there in about forty minutes. twenty if he ran. instead he waited two days before he began his journey. when he finally showed up, his friend had been dead, in the grave, for four days.
-
why?
-
"it is for god‚Äôs glory so that god‚Äôs son may be glorified through it.‚Äù still, he wept over what had happened because he loved his friend dearly. he still cared about what his people were going through. jesus wept. the shortest verse in the bible makes the biggest impact because he still weeps for us.
-
jesus weeps for us for when we get dumped.
jesus weeps for us when we get bullied.
jesus weeps for us when we feel lonely and hopeless.
jesus weeps for us when we lose a baby.
jesus weeps for the children in africa, india, and thailand.
jesus weeps for the orphans and widows.
jesus weeps for the ones who just received bad news from their doctor.
jesus weeps for the mother who buries her son.
jesus weeps for anyone with claim to the #metoo movement.
jesus weeps for the girl in the high school bathroom who feels like she doesn't have options.
jesus weeps for the boy who is too afraid to speak up because his father might beat him again.
jesus weeps for you.
jesus loves you so much that he weeps for you when you struggle, when you hurt, when you don't understand. 
jesus weeps because he cares.
-
so, the next time you think, "why does god let bad things happen?" remember "it is for god‚Äôs glory so that god‚Äôs son may be glorified through it.‚Äù but also remember that he cares. remember that you aren't alone, because he has already gone before us.
-
sometimes it's impossible for us to see what god is doing behind the scenes. but one thing you can be sure of, he has a plan. in the end it will bring glory to the kingdom and to the king.

queen furra was a powerful ruler for the sidama people, in ethiopia. today, she is remembered for her belief that women are capable being in power. queen furra demonstrated her belief by establishing an administration dominated by women. growing up, she saw sidama women facing injustice by manipulative sidama men. when furra‚Äôs administration was changing sidama people‚Äôs life while defining the role of women, sidama men teamed up to kill her. after killing furra, sidama men destroyed furra‚Äôs work to prevent influence and legacy. like furra, there many ethiopian women who helped to build the ethiopia we know today; however, the cultural outlooks prevented ethiopian women from receiving any credit they deserve. sign the petition and help fight the injustice ethiopian women face.  #metooethiopa #grlpwr  #ethiopia #africa #metoo #women #2019 #blackhistory

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaign‚Äôs use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there ‚Äúcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheating‚Äù. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesday‚Äôs hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: ‚Äúwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of people‚Äôs profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.‚Äù documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers‚Äô facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook‚Äôs ‚Äúplatform policy‚Äù allowed only collection of friends‚Äô data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook‚Äôs role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate ‚Äúinformation warfare‚Äù against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takers‚Äô facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebook‚Äôs ‚Äúplatform policy‚Äù allowed only collection of friends‚Äô data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for adveising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebook‚Äôs role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robe mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate ‚Äúinformation warfare‚Äù against the us.

text:
reporting a rapist is a personal decision.
a campus administrator once said to me in regard to why i was pursuing a legal case against my rapist, "i understand you are coming forward because you don't want him to hurt others." while this seems like a nice sentiment, it's not. it places responsibility on me for his actions.
i am doing this for me. i am doing this so i can get justice for what happened to me. i had a right to choose what path was right for me and in the end that was coming forward. but i also had the right to choose to not report my rape. his actions are not contingent upon my silence. i refuse to bear the burden and responsibility of his past and future actions. 
we need to stop placing responsibility on victims and start placing responsibilities on rapists. considering the reality of our justice system, it is understandable that many survivors don't come forward. 
so no, i did not come forward to protect others. i am doing this for me. 
survivors have enough responsibility to bear, they don't need to bear the responsibility of their rapists' actions too. this doesn't mean that the chance of others being victimized wasn't a factor in my decision, it just means that survivors shouldn't be pressured into doing something that is not right for them just because others might be hurt.

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
when i wanted to report my rape to the police, i spoke on the phone with an police officer. and i do absolutely respect and support the police and i really don‚Äôt want to talk them down or anything... but they really dissappointed me in my case. 
so i was on the phone with the police officer, and i told him what had happened and that i wanted to report it. after hearing my story, the officer told me that it would be useless to report it because there wasn‚Äôt really enough evidence for them to investigate. 
this made me feel so unimportant.. almost as if it wasn‚Äôt important enough for them to start an investigation... they didn‚Äôt even try to get security cameras or anything.... i felt like i was being dramatic and just had to get over myself and move on. 
being honest, i think that if i would‚Äôve actually reported the crime, it would have helped me ‚Äúmove on‚Äù. that way i could at least feel like i could have a chance to get justice. or that i was important enough to conduct an investigation for.
i am so sad to think that this is still a reality nowadays... #mentalhealthawareness #metoo #rapesurvivor #ptsdawareness #ptsdrecovery

internet censorship has already started.
youtube has announced plans to permanently blacklist all videos it deems ‚Äúconspiratorial‚Äù from its platform. 
the video platform has finally caved in to pressure from far-left journalists who have been aggressively lobbying the company to ban content creators, and videos, that go against the mainstream narrative.

venturebeat.com reports: while the google-owned video giant has often courted controversy over some of the content that finds its way onto its platform, the company does have policies in place that serve as a guide to what is, and isn‚Äôt, allowed. some of these videos are eventually taken down. but then, there is content that youtube refers to as ‚Äúborderline‚Äù ‚Äî it doesn‚Äôt breach any policies, per se, but at the same time, many people would rather not see them.

and that is the content youtube is now looking to scrub from users‚Äô ‚Äúup next‚Äù queue.

rabbit hole

anyone who‚Äôs spent even a short time on youtube will know its addictive nature: what begins as an innocent 30-second session to watch a prank skit sent by their buddy descends into a rabbit-hole of neverending autoplay ‚Äúrecommendations‚Äù served up by the data-powered internet gods.

it‚Äôs in youtube‚Äôs interests to keep you there, of course, as the more you‚Äôre on its platform the more ads you‚Äôll likely view. the company also recently added swiping to the mobile app ‚Äî to make it easier for you to skip to the next recommended video. ‚ôª ‚ôª ‚ôª ‚ôª ‚ôª ü¶Öü¶Öüá∫üá∏üî¥‚ö™Ô∏èüîµüá∫üá∏ü¶Öü¶Ö#iglifethrupics #metoo #maga #sheepnomore #feminismiscancer #ŒºŒøŒªœâŒΩŒªŒ±Œ≤Œµ  #christian

text:
day 1 of f.l.a.g course  course was very successful! today‚Äôs topic was strikes (how to do and how to defend) and sexual harassment 
theory: 5 stages of self defence, how to overcome fear, how to minimise risk of being targeted. 
next week we will be focussing on how to respond to a controlling attack (grabs chokes, pins, holds) and combining grabs and strikes and how to defend 
final week is how to use everything and anything as a weapon or equaliser or to aid your defence, and basics of weapons defence. 
if you want to drop in for one of these topics please do it‚Äôs ¬£25 on the door.

on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,¬†wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrested¬†earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
üëèreal talk aheadüëè
i mentioned on this last episode that i was probably never going to download a dating app ever again üôÖüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è after getting out of a relationship i rebounded hard on dating apps & had flings for a few months that left me feeling... blah...then i had this long distance thing that just settled the fact that i did not want to date...for awhile. 
when i‚Äôm single i‚Äôm known for being a serial dater. i‚Äôm an extrovert & it‚Äôs free food/drinks, so win/win for me üíÅüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è something about being done with casual dating this time & needing a change felt very different. i surmised that apps had to be the issue because that‚Äôs how i‚Äôd met people. i‚Äôd grown up w/ my mom telling me, ‚Äúyou don‚Äôt want to meet a guy in a bar‚Äù so an app seemed like the better option.. or did it ü§î

i didn‚Äôt feel like i found ‚Äúquality‚Äùon apps. at best, guys wanted to take me on a few dates & try to sleep w/ me & then one of us end things awkwardly/ghost each other. üò¨ or at worst have a half-assed conversation w/ me. i‚Äôm at a place in my life where i know what i want & need. i want a real relationship w/ someone i can build something with. back when i deleted the apps off my phone i didn‚Äôt think there was a way to find quality on apps like @bumble/@hinge 
on another point, i take my career, this podcast, and my non-profit @girlpowerhoursa very seriously. if it doesn‚Äôt add value to my life, it gets cut. at that point in time, dating was an emotional drain. quite simply, i just had too many good things going for me to get bogged down with negative. üíÅüèº‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è fast forward several months, & i still found myself in that place of not wanting anything casual & wanting something more serious (as a person who‚Äôs known for changing her mind on the daily is a pretty big deal) so, after relistening to my recording w/ @girlgetyourrootsdone and knowing i was in the right headspace i decided to redownload my apps again but do things as much my own way and as authentically as possible this go around. i limit myself to so many swipes and convos a day. i only swipe right if i‚Äôm genuinely intrigued. i‚Äôm as upfront as possible about what i want.ü§ó continued below ‚¨áÔ∏è‚¨áÔ∏è‚¨áÔ∏è

text: ivy muslim conference 2019‚úåüèæthe past two days were a emotional roller coaster. i enjoyed sharing a ~4 hr (each way) van ride, coffee break at barnes and nobles, getting jealous of yale students for having amazing food options, fitting 6 people on a common room floor, listening to the inspiring journey of @mokhtar_alkhanshali , eating at @thehalalguys ,listening to love poetries, taking a bathroom break at the spookiest welcome house with these amazing people! there were moments of discomfort and rage: a #metoo discussion table with all male students, a conservative speaker spewing hate but getting a leeway only because she is a woman, not having the opportunity to have constructive debate! after all the anxiety and laughter, i have learned a lot alhamdulillah and have reaffirmed my passion to serve the marginalized communities: gender-based violence survivors, lgbtq+ community, people with mental health issues. i hope the next conference will be more welcoming of these minority groups and create opportunities for constructive discussions.
name: Sirajum Munira Sandhi
tweet_full: ivy muslim conference 2019‚úåüèæthe past two days were a emotional roller coaster. i enjoyed sharing a ~4 hr (each way) van ride, coffee break at barnes and nobles, getting jealous of yale students for having amazing food options, fitting 6 people on a common room floor, listening to the inspiring journey of @mokhtar_alkhanshali , eating at @thehalalguys ,listening to love poetries, taking a bathroom break at the spookiest welcome house with these amazing people! there were moments of discomfort and rage: a #metoo discussion table with all male students, a conservative speaker spewing hate but getting a leeway only because she is a woman, not having the opportunity to have constructive debate! after all the anxiety and laughter, i have learned a lot alhamdulillah and have reaffirmed my passion to serve the marginalized communities: gender-based violence survivors, lgbtq+ community, people with mental health issues. i hope the next conference will be more welcoming of these minority groups and create opportunities for constructive discussions.

text:
the thing about sex, as far back as ancient egypt, is that *women* had as much ownership over desire as men, which later met it's demise in the victorian era, and never really regained it's footing
.

its alarming that people have become so simple as to *charge* men with the belief that these behaviors can exist in singularity, when no such thing is humanly possible
.

enter the grotesquely ignorant white lady #metoo movement: conversations about personal comfort erected next to conversations about rape, sex and molestation, all of which are indicative of grave mental illness
.

i just imagine meg newman and meg mantia (that ignorant, untrained food photographer) scapegoating the greater world bc they're culturally, sexually, illiterate, shaming anyone who dares to complicate human discourse
.

it's pathetic, it's white, and it's up from a brief history that *also* doesn't allow bike riding
.

white people, particularly white girls -- into their 60s!!, are *collectively* problematic in their *own* assumptions of their lasting ingenuity, bc although it's become an internalized implicit psychology, its nothing more then a *currency*, exchanged for a unique brand of culturally exclusive american protection, which begins with sexuality (think white men hanging black men on behalf of saving american purity, personified in the innocent white girl)
.

white girls, like carol from the housewives, truly believe that harvey winstiens (sp?) mention of "cumming when his nipples are rubbed" is equal to cases of *childhood rape*. why does she believe this? because she's a misogynist, activating white male sexism to both exoticize and protect her, depending on her mood
.

it's sick, but far more then that? it's learned
.

white girls can't be uncomfortable. they think it's an inherent right to find universal, unchallenged safety in the world. it's gross, and a full denial of a base respect expected of an adult on behalf of cultural diversity -- yes, sexuality is cultural
.

it's like meg newman and her *need* to publish the same book over and over again til her relationship to her sense of comfort becomes militia. it's tacky, and it's not at all aligned with power, but fear

text:
hi friends

i‚Äôm going silent for a lil while to process everything that‚Äôs happened in the past year. i hid so much from so many people. 
a year ago this week, i was sexually assaulted. i was scared into silence and truly felt that no one would believe me. my inability to process what happened led to a serious drinking problem and prescription drug abuse - i detailed it in an essay you can find on my website if that‚Äôs your thing. 
this picture was taken the very next week, if i recall correctly. don‚Äôt assume that because someone‚Äôs outwardly flowering that they‚Äôre not withering inside.

i‚Äôm going to just put my head down and focus on myself for the first time in a long while. it‚Äôs fun and all to break it until it breaks. it broke. let‚Äôs fix it

lots of love and endless blessings to all of you wonderful people. keep the faith. play the long game. #metoo

text:
"for us and for our salvation he came down from heaven, was incarnate of the holy spirit and the virgin mary and became truly human. for our sake he was crucified under pontius pilate; he suffered death and was buried. on the third day he rose again in accordance with the scriptures; he ascended into heaven and is seated at the right hand of the father. he will come again in glory to judge the living and the dead, and his kingdom will have no end." -a segment of the nicene creed

as i read this i'm reminded as i was by last week's reflection on the nicene creed, of god's immanence- his nearness. both the incarnation and the indwelling of the holy spirit profoundly reflect to me god's love for us and his desire to be near us. these truths are such beautiful and moving aspects of christian theology!

i'm also reminded of phillippians 2- paul's powerful description of jesus, who is god himself, becoming human and suffering for our salvation.

these days, because of #metoo, #churchtoo, black lives matter and some of my personal experiences, issues related to power are often on my mind. for me, the incarnation, as reflected in philippians 2, is the ultimate tribute to the importance and power of humility and servant leadership in the church. i hope this reality would cause those of us who stray from christ's humble, sacrificial example to repent and return to the path he laid out for us in this regard.

text:
*not slimmingworld related.. sorry* ... i never talk about this but i need to and i hope people on here can be understanding... today, i saw him. i saw the 'man' that ruined my youth, ruined my sanity, my life for the past nearly 8 years. i walked past the person that took my innocence, who lead me to a path of self-hatred and guilt, being bullied, anxiety, low mood. but, did he even look at me? no, because to him i'm nothing. i haven't changed his life, i didn't take anything from him. that's what made me so angry, angry enough to write this post. why have i spent 8 years suffering because of someone who i am nothing to? he may have caused me 8 years of pain but i'm damned if he's going to cause me another 8 years. one day i plan to report it, not when i'm 'brave enough' or 'strong enough' but when i'm ready. i dont really know why ive decided to open myself up right now, but im sick of hiding. i just wanted to put this out here and thank you for reading part of my story ‚ù§
.
.
.
.
. .
#metoo #mentalhealth #1in4mentalhealth #1in5 #strong #brave #unite #powerfulwoman #loveyourself #itstime #mystory #womenpower #selfcare #selfworth #empower
